    "content": "<p>Identify product $$(Z)$$ in the series, of reaction</p>\n<p>$$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{HBr}} X \\xrightarrow{a q . \\mathrm{KOH}} Y \\xrightarrow[\\mathrm{I}_2 \\text { excess }]{\\mathrm{Na}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3} Z$$</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{I}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{CHI}_3$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}$$"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Let's go through the sequence of reactions step by step to identify the final product $$(Z)$$.</p>\n\n<p>Step 1: $$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{HBr}} X$$</p>\n\n<p>The addition of hydrogen bromide (HBr) to ethene ($$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}_2$$) follows Markovnikov's rule, forming bromoethane ($$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{Br}$$) as the product.</p>\n\n<p>$$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}_2 + \\mathrm{HBr} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{Br}$$</p>\n\n<p>So, $$X$$ is $$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{Br}$$.</p>\n\n<p>Step 2: $$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{Br} \\xrightarrow{a q . \\mathrm{KOH}} Y$$</p>\n\n<p>When bromoethane reacts with aqueous potassium hydroxide (KOH), nucleophilic substitution occurs, converting bromoethane to ethanol ($$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH}$$).</p>\n\n<p>$$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{Br} + \\mathrm{KOH} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH} + \\mathrm{KBr}$$</p>\n\n<p>So, $$Y$$ is $$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH}$$.</p>\n\n<p>Step 3: $$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH} \\xrightarrow[\\mathrm{I}_2 \\text{ excess }]{\\mathrm{Na}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3} Z$$</p>\n\n<p>Ethanol (ethyl alcohol) reacts with iodine ($$\\mathrm{I}_2$$) in the presence of sodium carbonate ($$\\mathrm{Na}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3$$) to form iodoform ($$\\mathrm{CHI}_3$$). This reaction is known as the iodoform test, which is a common qualitative test for the presence of methyl ketones and ethanol.</p>\n\n<p>$$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH} + 4\\mathrm{I}_2 + \\mathrm{Na}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{CHI}_3 + 5\\mathrm{NaI} + \\mathrm{HCOONa} + 2\\mathrm{H}_2\\mathrm{O}$$</p>\n\n<p>So, $$Z$$ is $$\\mathrm{CHI}_3$$ (iodoform).</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the correct answer is:</p>\n\n<p>Option C: $$\\mathrm{CHI}_3$$</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2023,
    "yearKey": "bitsat-2023",
    "difficulty": null
  },
